

Macao recorded an estimated value of 2.2 billion patacas (275 million US dollars) in retail sales in the third quarter, a year-on-year rise of 23 percent, according to official statistics issued here on Wednesday.

The figures from the government-run Statistics and Census Service (SCS) showed that motor vehicles sales accounted for 16 percent of the total estimated value of retail sales in the quarter,followed by sales of goods in supermarkets (11 percent) and in department stores (11 percent) and sales of watches, clocks and jewelry (10 percent).

The SCS attributes the rocketing retail sales growth mainly to "the marked increases" in the sales of motor vehicles.

Around 85 percent of the local retailers forecast increased or flat sales prices for the fourth quarter, according to the SCS statistics.

